05703nam a22008535i 9781501756429DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020043173  a97815017564297 a10.1515/97815017564292doi  a(DE-B1597)571908  a(OCoLC)1198988838  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aD639.D45bK54 2021 7aPOL0340002bisacsh04a940.3/12231 aKier, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWar and Democracy :bLabor and the Politics of Peace /cElizabeth Kier. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (258 p.) :b2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Mobilizing Labor for War and Its Implications for Democracy -- t2. Disciplining Italian Labor -- t3. Managing British Labor -- t4. Choosing a Mobilization Strategy: A Counterfactual Analysis -- t5. Italian Labor’s Revolutionary Socialism -- t6. British Labor’s Moderate Socialism -- t7. Compliance, Revenge, and the Rise of Italian Fascism -- t8. Revisiting Competing Accounts, and the Failure of British Reform -- t9. Conclusion: Bringing the Politics of War into the Politics of Peace -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aChallenging conventional wisdom that mass-mobilization warfare fosters democratic reform and expands economic, social, and political rights, War and Democracy reexamines the effects of war on domestic politics by focusing on how wartime states either negotiate with or coerce organized labor, policies that profoundly affect labor's beliefs and aspirations. Because labor unions frequently play a central role in advancing democracy and narrowing inequalities, their wartime interactions with the state can have significant consequences for postwar politics.Comparing Britain and Italy during and after World War I, Elizabeth Kier examines the different strategies each government used to mobilize labor for war and finds that total war did little to promote political, civil, or social rights in either country. Italian unions anticipated greater worker management and a "land to the peasants" program as a result of their wartime service; British labor believed its wartime sacrifices would be repaid with "homes for heroes" and the extension of social rights. But Italy's unjust and coercive policies radicalized Italian workers (prompting a fascist backlash) and Britain's just and conciliatory policies paradoxically undermined broader democratization in Britain. In critiquing the mainstream view that total war advances democracy, War and Democracy reveals how politics during the war transforms societal actors who become crucial to postwar political settlements and the prospects for democratic reform.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDemocracy. 0aLabor movementxPolitical aspectszGreat Britain. 0aLabor movementxPolitical aspectszItaly. 0aPolitics and war. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xInfluence. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xSocial aspectszItaly. 4aLabor History. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aWest European History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Peace.2bisacsh  aThe effect of war on democracy, How justice affects democratic reform, Revolutionary politics in Italy, War and the making of British reform, World war I and democracy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073908408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9